<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06050070 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06050070 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  QA; PSYCHOLOGY; BEHAVIOR; RESULT; WAR  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Q I will soon become the guardian for my nieces and nephews. Their dad is inSaudi Arabia, and their mom will be going there soon. I am concerned about theemotional well-being of these three kids.; -- Amie Skipper, San Jose  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SEPARATION TRAUMATIC FOR KIDS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  War in the GulfCoping with the conflict  </MEMO><TEXT>  A The central issue for kids, when something bad happens, is that they feel atfault. Children often feel that parents go away because the child was bad. Itis important to tell the kids that they are good, lovable kids and that no oneleft because they were bad.;    The feeling strikes at the heart ofself-esteem and self-worth. &quot;It is also important to let them know they willbe safe and that you are committed to taking care of them. Explain that theirparents were ordered to go away by the president, that separation is temporaryand even that their parents will come back.;    Remember they can't understandall about Saddam and Bush. They are filled with rage, longing andpowerlessness. They need to be able to talk about these feelings. Let them.;   Look out for stress-related behavior: bed wetting, crying for no reason,hostility, a lack of interest in school and any radical changes in behavior.;   Also watch your own feelings. If you find yourself feeling frustration don'tbe shy about getting help and support from your friends, family orprofessionals.; HAVE A QUESTION?; If you have questions about your emotionalreactions to the Persian Gulf crisis, ask Gail Jones Sanchez, a Milpitascounselor who specializes in stress. Include your name, city and phone number.Call us at (408) 920-5926 or fax questions at (408) 920-5244.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910219  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  283  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday February 19, 199100050070,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>